<center><div style="border: 1px solid white; font-size:15px; width:300px; padding:5px 5px; background:black; font-family:Fraunces">[[Long Way Down#fullscreen-2|<span style="color:white">Previous Tale: Long Way Down</span>]]</div></center>



<div style="background: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b); padding: 5px; margin:2em">
<div style="background: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b); padding: 5px; box-shadow: 0px 5px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 1)">
<div style="background: black; border: 5px solid transparent; border-image: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b) 1 round; no-repeat; border-radius: 2px; padding: 20px; box-shadow: 0px 5px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 1); color: white; font-size:13px; font-family:Merriweather">
The artificial stars of studio lights baked the stage Ava and Clover stepped on. A cascading dance of color washed out the paleness of their skin. Once rich in life, the lack of sunlight present in many levels made their features paled and gloomy. With false suns beaming down on them, Clover took a moment to stand in the light, basking in brightness they had grown alien to. With a sigh filling a quiet theater with sound, they looked towards their friend, whose eyes were thinned in the starry scene. Ava squinted past the studio lights and to the decadent seats. This wasn't some high-school auditorium, after all. 

"You know," Clover started, moving closer to the familiar girl, "I wished I could be an actor, was a big deal to see people like Oprah Winfrey and Whoopi Goldberg become popular." Clover spoke with distance in their eyes, seeing thousands of yards through the few curtains ahead of them. Though when Ava moved her hand over Clover's eyes, they snapped back to reality. "Where was I?"

"Wanting to be an actor, yea?"

"Oh, right. Well I tried to be one for the longest time, but it just never worked out. Maybe I'm just an idiot." Clover laughed, an Ava responded with a smile too. Perhaps a little more, as it trickled up into a restrained chuckle. Clover always knew their laugh to be infectious, and to see it proven again brought on some assurance. Clover felt their confidence soar each time. It was pride hard fought in the struggle of survival. 

Ava descended onto one knee as the laughter dissipated, pulling their bag off their back. It landed before her in a thud, with sounds of splashing water and bags of trail mix complimenting the mess. "Are we stopping here?" Clover questioned, looking down at their friend. Ava only gave them a shrug.

[[File:StageTaleImage.png|center|350px]]


"You tell me."

Clover looked around, giving a content sigh as they sat down. 

"Yea, I guess we are." 

Their silence sat in the air, daintily stringing their bond. An air of string was weaker than one of firm tangibility, and as Clover watched Ava quietly shift through her supplies, their head tilted slightly. Something confused Clover, and it didn't seem they were ready to give it up.

''They're watching for an answer'', August told himself, fishing through supplies before he finds a bottle of Almond Water. He took two out, tossing one to his friend. He watched as something seemed to click in Clover's head, as soon as his friend caught the drink.

"You're looking kind of tense there, Ava." Ava sighed, nodding as she shifted to a more comfortable seating position. The canister of Almond Water cracks open and she takes a swig.
</div>
</div>
</div>



{{Quote|Hey, Ava. August—whatever. Can you please call me back? Ever since this whole, like, thing, I've been worried about you for months. You know how worried I get, right, Ava? ''click''|December 13th, 2013.}} 



{{Quote|I know you're paranoid and you think I'm going to hurt you but I'd never do that to my sweet girl, you'd know that the best sweetie, I'm sure about that... ''click''|December 13th, 2013.}}



{{Quote|Ava. Please. Call me back, you clearly misunderstood me and I don't want to lose you, you're my everything. Y-you really are, you know? I love you Avee... ''click''|December 14th, 2013.}}



<div style="background: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b); padding: 5px; margin:2em">
<div style="background: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b); padding: 5px; box-shadow: 0px 5px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 1)">
<div style="background: black; border: 5px solid transparent; border-image: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b) 1 round; no-repeat; border-radius: 2px; padding: 20px; box-shadow: 0px 5px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 1); color: white; font-size:13px; font-family:Merriweather">
"Yea, sort of." The sudden shift seemed to worry Clover some, as August pushed his voice down to as deep as he could make it in that moment. He watched silently, and judgmentally as Clover moved away. "That's why I'm tense." August drank some more of the Almond Water, sighing as he looked to the rows of seats before them both. Continuous rows of red built a silent tension between them both. Needles stabbed his skin every time he heard his old name. It wasn't simply pain he was feeling, it was anger. A frustration that formed from such a simple and consistent failure. He had restated his name time and time again.

"I-I don't follow. You're being weird... can I not be discomforted by that?" Clover couldn't look at Ava for the time, and only followed their eyes to the rows of seats. Something in them felt wrong, and why? They tried to dig through their mind about what they thought of Ava. They knew Ava was a man, always did. 

"When you starting going through with it," Clover started again, moving to sit at the edge of the stage, "I was happy for you. Always was. But you also started to change." August cocked his head to the side some, though Clover didn't notice. "More than just physically, but emotionally. You were tougher and more questionable. Maybe threatening is the right word..." August slowly moved closer to Clover, sliding across the ground slowly and with concern. "I don't know, maybe I'm in the wrong. But sometimes I miss when you were easier to talk to. I was less worried around ''Ava'' than I was August." Clover sighed, pressing their head into their hands. August didn't move all the way over, instead stopping an arms reach away from Clover.

[[File:Audience.png|center|350px]]


For a bit he pondered on what Clover told him, only feeling worse as it simmered. The stew of his mind grew grotty and gooey as it stirred. But what could he even say? For the few minutes of silence, August tried every arrangement of words he could think up. Eventually, he had to be honest with himself and Clover.

"You are. You are very much in the wrong." A deep lump formed in the bottom of August's throat as he spoke, slowly his eyes shifted back to the rest of the stage, leaving his words to bubble in Clover's brain. He knew it frustrated Clover to get that response, but as he slid away he caught them think through it. It left a pained look on their face, as August expected. Their face contorted from indignation, to deep thought, and then pity. Slowly it consumed their mind. They weren't the people they once knew, profoundly different in mannerisms and form. August dutifully acknowledged it, and seeing them struggle made the lump even greater. "I do want to care about you Clover, that much doesn't change for me. But this is a relationship, and I'm fine with letting it go." August moved back to his bag, unlatching the bedspread and laying it out. 

The sleeping bag was a baby blue, and he bought it from [[Level 4|Base Opportunity]] some time back. Like many things, it was a change he learned to tolerate. Yet it barely fit him still, August always was taller than most girls he knew. Now, he was just an above average guy. Funny how validating that felt back then. Trapped in their mind, Clover barely heard August mutter "night" before turning away from them to sleep. The next minutes were of a delicate silence, with only the sounds of entities in the distance filling the auditorium. Almost too perfect. When Clover snapped out of their thoughts, a feeling of being watched prickled down their neck. It was one they felt only some time ago, when they ran into August. With the air seemingly directing them, Clover turned to look to where they thought someone was staring, to see their eyes being met.

"Ava?"
</div>
</div>
</div>



{{Quote|Why are you being so difficult with me? What part of this are you not understanding Ava, and if I seem mad I am. Where are you? Come home, now... ''CLICK''|December 14th, 2013.}}



{{Quote|I must be such a bad mom... After all these years of sacrifice and effort and this is what I get, Ava? Immaturity? ''CLICK''|December 15th, 2013}}



{{Quote|You don't respect me or your father at all Avee. Don't call me back then, see if I care... ''SLAM''|December 15th, 2013.}}



<div style="background: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b); padding: 5px; margin:2em">
<div style="background: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b); padding: 5px; box-shadow: 0px 5px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 1)">
<div style="background: black; border: 5px solid transparent; border-image: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b) 1 round; no-repeat; border-radius: 2px; padding: 20px; box-shadow: 0px 5px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 1); color: white; font-size:13px; font-family:Merriweather">
"You ended up here too?" the figure stepped out from the darkness, walking through the soft haze of lights. Clover raced over to hug them, receiving one back in exchange. The silence became far more comfortable, resonating with the snoring of August to feel more like speaking to a close friend than meeting a stranger. For a moment, Clover forgot about the other person they were camping with, as the stress of life itself seemed to slowly unwind again. Spools of thread containing thoughts and feelings slowly spun, letting it slink out of its chamber like the charmer's snake.

"Yea, somehow" Clover sighed, thinking back to their first arrival to [[Level 0|the lobby]], the winding mesh of yellow stained walls. Their brain trickled through each sect of reality they had to traverse though until finally meeting people. A cold world they had to learn to understand. It wasn't all bad, at least as much as Clover could remember, much of their time in the Backrooms was slowly washed away as the banality made holding on to certain events difficult. For now, it wasn't much worth talking about, maybe at a later point when they grow more comfortable in their new reality.

Clover's thoughts eventually would shift away from their own experience, and they'd let go of Ava. First there was a plan smile on their face, then they noticed some oddities. 

[[File:Nottobetrusted.png|center|350px]]


Perhaps the hair was a little shorter than Clover remembered it to be, she looked more confident than her standard body language. Ava was more mature, so it was possible she had also grown to be more confident. Yet, as Clover wanted to accept these changes, they were left with some questions.

"How come you have no supplies?"

"Oh I was camping in a different part of Level 444, left my stuff there to snoop around and see if I could find anyone helpful." Ava shrugged off the question, looking past Clover to the set up they had. It wasn't much. Two bedrolls, one a soft gray, and the other a navy blue, were laid out under one of the dimming stage lights. Bags with supplies were kept nearby, and in Clover's case, was propped up to lay their head on it. Perhaps it was tougher than the usual pillows back home, but Clover didn't have much of an option. 

"If that's the case, We might have some extra sitting about." Though as Clover fully turned to look at both their and August's supply, they shifted to look at the sleeping man. Their thoughts raced to catch up at that moment, and Clover turned back to look at Ava. With a point of their finger and accusations in Clover's eyes, they spoke again. "Why is there two of you now?"
</div>
</div>
</div>



{{Quote|I'm not going to keep feeding this leftist bullshit Ava. I don't care how much damage you do to yourself, you are a woman. You make me and your father look terrible with these games, and I can't believed we raised such a damn brat. ''click''|December 16th, 2013.}}



{{Quote|You can't even be bothered to answer the phone we fucking pay for. When you get back here, you will be grounded, useless kid... ''SLAM''|December 16th, 2013.}}



{{Quote|I have nothing else to say. You're a unreliable, undependable, self absorbed person Ava. I'm so discouraged and disgusted with what you've become. ''SLAM''|December 19th, 2013.}}



<div style="background: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b); padding: 5px; margin:2em">
<div style="background: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b); padding: 5px; box-shadow: 0px 5px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 1)">
<div style="background: black; border: 5px solid transparent; border-image: linear-gradient(45deg, #f2de6b, #f2de6b) 1 round; no-repeat; border-radius: 2px; padding: 20px; box-shadow: 0px 5px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 1); color: white; font-size:13px; font-family:Merriweather">
"I don't follow," Ava mumbled back, her head softly tilted to the side, looking past Clover's pointing.

"I meet Ava... in a different level. Back when I first entered the Backrooms. I think it was Level 922, that's what I was told." Clover slurred through their monologue, looking at a very confused Ava. "But there, their name was August. I think they're trans now? But then how is there two of you?"

Ava thought for a moment, as a chilling breeze ran itself across Clover's body. They couldn't quite tell where it came from, more like air pushing itself closer to them. It felt like the wind was trying to suffocate them, or trap them in this confusion. They looked at Ava, then at August. Back and forth like the pendulum on a grandfather clock. But this wasn't to count seconds, it was a question that ticked away, slowly reaching its countdown.

"Well, how can I prove to you I'm the real one?" Ava walked past Clover, now standing between them and August's body. Ava had positioned themself further into the darkness, shielding away some of their inconsistencies. It was a deliberate ploy, but one that Clover had no understanding of. For a moment, Ava reveled in the perfect scheme, two bodies with one disguise. Yet the emotions were pushed down again, festering and rotting to become a moldy excitement. But now, she was faced with the hardest part, proving it. 

"When is my birthday?" Clover hesitantly started.

"September 19th," Ava responded with a smile.

"What's my dad's name?"

"David; your mom's name is Lou."

"What school did we go to?"

"Curtis High." Clover was rendered silent, their mind freshly blanked at the speed of Ava's responses. Ava pulled her arms to her chest, sighing. It was almost pathetic how easy it was, but now was not the time to mock her. "So, am I the real Ava?"

[[File:shadowgun.png|center|400px]]


{{Fullscreen
|padding=2rem
|number=1
|show= <span style="color:#f2de6b">"I think so"</span>
|hide= <span style="color:red">Go back</span>
|content={{Blurbackground|file=Black-Screen.png}}
<div style="margin:10em; text-align:center">
"Then what about August?" Clover pondered, looking towards the sleeping man. Was this just a stranger who they attached themselves to? Was it actually Ava? Clover pinched themself, hoping to wake up from this confusion, clawing at the reins of reality as they begged it to be freed. Yet the shackles remained strong, enforcing a pained truth upon them. This was reality. and they were deceived in some manner. But how?

"My guess, is that he's a skin-stealer.." Clover gasped stepping away from Ava and August and into the lights of the stage. Ava moved over to Clover's bag, pulling out a blade. "I'm sorry I have to do this in front of you... you can close your eyes if you'd like." Ava spoke softly and assuredly, and Clover did what they were asked to do.

<big> CRUNCH </big>

Clover withdrew even further from them, as the sound of gore sent shivers on their spine. Their ears were left to witness the madness, yet still too much for Clover to bear. They heard the sounds of panic and aggression, grunts and yelps as August was pulled awake. The sounds of the struggle played out on a stage to an audience of none, a perfect symphony with none to attend.

<big> BANG BANG BANG </big>

Then it became silent. And Clover hesitated to peek. Slowly, their eyes opened. Standing there was August, a red coating on his shirt, collar, and face. On the ground, Ava, with an almost perfectly clear liquid leaking out. It looked thicker than water,  but Clover wasn't interested in making sure of it. As August turned to look at Clover, her face was painted red with embarrassment, and words choked themselves on their lips.

"Sorry..." was all Clover could choke out.



